;
; wAddressHi     dwAddressLo       dwCacheAreaSize,	dwScanAreaSize
;


;Notes:
;
; All blank lines or lines beginning with a simi-colon are considered "comment" lines
;
; The first (non-comment) line contains the quantity of Cache Areas
;
; Hexidecimal numbers need to begin with "0x"
;
; wAddressHi and dwAddressLo represent the starting address (48 bit memory map address)
; of the mem map area to be cached.
;
; dwCacheAreaSize is the number of bytes in the respective area to cache.
;
; dwScanAreaSize: when the scanner reads from the memory map, it should only do so in
; chunks that are <= 1536 (0x600) bytes. Therefore, areas that are much larger must be 
; divided into reasonable sized chunks. This "chunk" size is dwScanAreaSize. Also, the
; value of dwScanAreaSize should be evenly divisable by the number of bytes in the
; respective data type. For example, in the scratch Pad string area, each string 
; occupies 130 (0x82) bytes. Eight strings would occupy 1040 (ox410) bytes, which is 
; less than or equal to 1536. Therefore, 1040 is a reasonable value for dwScanAreaSize.
; As another example, in the Alarm Event Settings area, each "Alarm" occupies 128 (0x80)
; bytes. Eight Alarms would occupy 1024 (0x400) bytes, which is less than or equal to 
; 1536. Therefore, 1024 is a reasonable value for dwScanAreaSize. 
